Web Application Firewall (WAF)

An application is a program that performs specific tasks. We use many applications daily, like eBook readers, e-commerce platforms, email applications, etc. Web applications are stored on a remote server and delivered through a browser interface. Web applications are developed based on many different architectures. The following is a simple example.

 

Source - zoom in

Web applications undoubtedly play a massive role in our daily activities, from sharing photos to handling millions of business activities every second. A web application firewall (WAF) is a security solution that filters out malicious web traffic between a client and a web application.

The main difference between a traditional network firewall and a web application firewall is that a WAF better understands how web applications work and is designed to detect attacks related to the web core protocol, HTTP.

Most web application firewalls protect against a set of well-known web attacks, such as:

  • XSS (Cross-site scripting)
  • SQL Injection
  • LFI (Local file inclusion)
  • RFI (Remote file inclusion)
  • Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)
  • Directory Traversal
  • OS Command Injection
     

Figure - zoom in

A WAF can be a stand-alone hardware box, software, or a cloud platform. F5 is a well-known WAF vendor, and Sucuri is very popular for its cloud WAF model. 

One important thing to mention is that the security controls we discussed so far complement each other to build defense-in-depth protection, which means a layered approach to defending a network. It's wrong to assume that a WAF can replace a network firewall or IPS. Each has its strengths and weaknesses, and the network should be architected to minimize protection gaps.
